# __init__.py is a special file in Python that is used to indicate that the directory it is present in is a Python package.
#  It can be an empty file, but it can also contain initialization code for the package. 
# When you import a package, the __init__.py file is executed, and any code within it will be run. 
# This allows you to set up any necessary variables, functions, or classes that should be available when the package is imported.
#  Additionally, __init__.py can be used to specify which modules should be imported when the package is imported, 
# making it easier to manage the structure of your code.